C Programming – Complete Beginner to Advanced Guide

This guide is structured to take you from absolute beginner to advanced/expert level in C. Each section builds on the previous one, and code examples illustrate every concept. Use it for learning, revision, and interview preparation.

---

Part 1: Beginner (Fundamentals)

1.1 What is C?

· A general-purpose, procedural programming language.
· Created by Dennis Ritchie in 1972.
· Compiled language → source code is translated into machine code.
· Basis of modern operating systems (Unix, Linux, Windows kernel parts) and embedded systems.

1.2 Your First Program

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

· #include <stdio.h> – includes the Standard Input/Output library.
· int main() – the entry point of every C program.
· printf – prints formatted text to the console.
· return 0 – signals successful execution to the operating system.

1.3 Basic Data Types

Type Typical Size Example Values
int 4 bytes -2, 0, 42
float 4 bytes 3.14f, -0.001f
double 8 bytes 3.1415926535
char 1 byte 'A', 'z', '\n'
void – (absence of type)

Variables must be declared with a type:

```c
int age = 30;
float price = 19.99;
char grade = 'A';
```

1.4 Input and Output

```c
int num;
printf("Enter a number: ");
scanf("%d", &num);          // & means "address of"
printf("You entered: %d\n", num);
```

· %d – integer
· %f – float/double
· %c – character
· %s – string (character array)

1.5 Operators

· Arithmetic: +, -, *, /, % (modulo)
· Relational: ==, !=, <, >, <=, >=
· Logical: &&, ||, !
· Assignment: =, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=
· Increment/Decrement: ++, --

```c
int a = 5, b = 2;
int sum = a + b;        // 7
int mod = a % b;        // 1
int c = (a > b) && (a != 0);  // 1 (true)
a++;                    // a becomes 6
```

1.6 Control Flow

if-else

```c
if (age >= 18) {
    printf("Adult\n");
} else {
    printf("Minor\n");
}
```

switch

```c
switch (grade) {
    case 'A': printf("Excellent\n"); break;
    case 'B': printf("Good\n"); break;
    default:  printf("Try harder\n");
}
```

Loops

```c
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    printf("%d ", i);
}
while (x > 0) {
    // ...
}
do {
    // ...
} while (condition);
```

· break – exits the loop immediately.
· continue – skips to the next iteration.

1.7 Functions

· A block of code that performs a task.
· Declaration (prototype): tells the compiler about the function's existence.
· Definition: contains the actual body.

```c
// Declaration
int add(int a, int b);

// Definition
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
```

Call by value: a copy of the argument is passed (changes inside the function do not affect the original).

1.8 Arrays

```c
int numbers[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
numbers[0] = 15;                     // change first element
printf("%d\n", numbers[2]);          // 30
```

· Index starts at 0.
· Array size must be a constant (or dynamic allocation for runtime size).
· When passed to a function, an array decays to a pointer (size information lost).

1.9 Strings (Basics)

A string is an array of char terminated by '\0' (null character).

```c
char name[] = "Alice";  // automatically null-terminated
printf("%s", name);     // prints "Alice"
```

Input a string (beware of buffer overflow):

```c
char str[20];
scanf("%s", str);       // stops at whitespace
fgets(str, 20, stdin);  // safer, reads up to 19 chars + null
```

