Part 2: Intermediate (Core Concepts)

2.1 Pointers – The Foundation

A pointer stores the memory address of another variable.

```c
int x = 10;
int *ptr = &x;      // ptr holds the address of x
*ptr = 20;          // dereference: change x to 20
```

· & – address-of operator.
· * – dereference operator (access the value at the address).

2.2 Pointer Arithmetic

Adding an integer to a pointer advances it by n * sizeof(type).

```c
int arr[] = {1, 2, 3};
int *p = arr;       // points to arr[0]
p++;                // now points to arr[1]
printf("%d", *(p+1)); // prints arr[2]
```

2.3 Dynamic Memory Allocation

Allocate memory at runtime using malloc, calloc, realloc, and free it with free.

```c
#include <stdlib.h>
int *arr = (int*) malloc(5 * sizeof(int));
if (arr == NULL) { /* handle error */ }
arr[0] = 100;
free(arr);          // always free to avoid memory leak
```

· calloc(n, size) allocates and zero-initialises.
· realloc(ptr, newSize) changes the size of the allocated block.

2.4 Structures

Group related variables of different types.

```c
struct Student {
    char name[50];
    int id;
    float gpa;
};

struct Student s1 = {"Alice", 101, 3.8};
s1.gpa = 3.9;
struct Student *sp = &s1;
sp->id = 102;       // arrow operator for pointers
```

· Structures can be copied by assignment (s2 = s1), but be careful with embedded pointers (shallow copy).

2.5 Typedef

Create an alias for a type:

```c
typedef struct Student {
    char name[50];
    int id;
    float gpa;
} Student;

Student s;
```

2.6 File I/O

```c
FILE *fp = fopen("data.txt", "w");
if (fp == NULL) {
    perror("Error opening file");
    return 1;
}
fprintf(fp, "Hello, file!\n");
fclose(fp);
```

· Modes: "r" (read), "w" (write), "a" (append), "r+", "w+", "a+".
· Reading: fscanf, fgets, fread.
· Binary mode: "rb", "wb".

2.7 Preprocessor Directives

· #include – insert a header file.
· #define – macros.
· Conditional compilation: #ifdef, #ifndef, #if, #else, #endif.

```c
#define PI 3.14159
#define MAX(a,b) ((a) > (b) ? (a) : (b))
```

2.8 Recursion

A function calling itself. Must have a base case.

```c
int factorial(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}
```

Recursion can be replaced by iteration and often consumes more stack memory.

2.9 Multi‑file Programs

· Header files (.h) contain declarations and type definitions.
· Source files (.c) contain function definitions.
· Compile together: gcc main.c utils.c -o program.

Header guard:

```c
#ifndef MYHEADER_H
#define MYHEADER_H
// ... declarations
#endif
```

