Part 3: Advanced (Low‑Level & Complex Topics)

3.1 Memory Layout of a C Program

Every process has a structured address space:

```
High address
┌─────────────┐
│  Stack      │ ← grows downward (local variables, function frames)
├─────────────┤
│  Heap       │ ← grows upward (dynamic memory)
├─────────────┤
│  BSS        │ ← uninitialised global/static data (zeroed)
├─────────────┤
│  Data       │ ← initialised global/static data
├─────────────┤
│  Text       │ ← code (read‑only)
└─────────────┘
Low address
```

Understanding this helps debug stack overflows, memory leaks, and pointer errors.

3.2 Pointers – Advanced

Double pointers (int **) – pointers to pointers, used for modifying a pointer argument.

```c
void allocate(int **p) {
    *p = malloc(sizeof(int));
}
int *ptr = NULL;
allocate(&ptr);
```

Function pointers – store the address of a function.

```c
int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
int (*fp)(int, int) = add;  // or = &add
int result = fp(3, 4);
```

Use case: callback functions, state machines, qsort.

Void pointers (void *) – generic pointer, can point to any data type; cannot be dereferenced directly.

Const and pointers:

· const int *p – can’t modify the pointed value.
· int * const p – pointer itself is constant.
· const int * const p – both pointer and value are constant.

3.3 Bit Manipulation

Operators: & (AND), | (OR), ^ (XOR), ~ (NOT), <<, >>.

```c
unsigned int flags = 0;
flags |= (1 << 3);   // set bit 3
flags &= ~(1 << 3);  // clear bit 3
flags ^= (1 << 2);   // toggle bit 2
if (flags & (1 << 3)) { /* bit 3 set? */ }
```

Common tasks: counting set bits, checking power of two, swapping integers with XOR.

3.4 Structures – Padding & Alignment

Compilers add padding bytes to align members to their natural boundaries. This can make the structure size larger than the sum of its members.

· To minimise padding, order members from largest to smallest.
· offsetof(struct_name, member) gives the offset.
· Use __attribute__((packed)) in GCC to remove padding (may hurt performance).

3.5 Unions

A union overlays members in the same memory. Only one member holds a meaningful value at a time.

```c
union Data {
    int i;
    float f;
    char str[20];
};
union Data d;
d.i = 10;   // now d.f is garbage
```

3.6 Dynamic Memory – Deep Internals

· The heap manager (e.g., glibc’s malloc) uses data structures (free lists, bins) to track free blocks.
· Allocated blocks carry a header (size + flags) just before the returned pointer.
· free must be called exactly once per malloc; double‑free and use‑after‑free are undefined behaviour.

3.7 String Handling (Advanced)

Implement your own strcpy, strlen, strcat, etc. – a common interview task.

```c
char* my_strcpy(char *dest, const char *src) {
    char *start = dest;
    while ((*dest++ = *src++));
    return start;
}
```

Always ensure buffers are large enough and properly null‑terminated.

3.8 Input / Output Under the Hood

· FILE * is a typedef for a structure containing the file descriptor, buffer, flags, etc.
· Three buffering modes: fully buffered, line buffered, unbuffered.
· setvbuf can change buffering behaviour.

3.9 Preprocessor – Macros & Conditional Compilation

· Macros: textual substitution; beware of side effects.
· # (stringizing) and ## (token pasting) operators.
· Predefined macros: __LINE__, __FILE__, __DATE__, __STDC__.
· Include guards and #pragma once.

3.10 static and extern Keywords

· static global variable/function: internal linkage (visible only within the translation unit).
· static local variable: persistent across function calls.
· extern: declares a variable/function defined in another file.

