Part 4: Expert (Undefined Behaviour, Portability, Concurrency, Deep Internals)

4.1 Undefined, Unspecified, and Implementation‑Defined Behaviour

· Undefined behaviour: the standard imposes no requirements – anything can happen (e.g., signed integer overflow, dividing by zero, dereferencing NULL, out‑of‑bounds array access, modifying a string literal). The compiler may assume UB never occurs and optimise accordingly.
· Unspecified behaviour: multiple possibilities, the compiler may choose (e.g., evaluation order of function arguments).
· Implementation‑defined behaviour: similar to unspecified, but the compiler must document its choice (e.g., size of int, sign of char).

Knowing UB is crucial for writing robust, portable C code and for interview scenarios.

4.2 Advanced Pointer Declarations (The “Right‑Left” Rule)

Parse complex declarations like:

```c
int *(*(*arr[5])(int))[10];
// arr is an array[5] of pointers to functions taking int and returning pointer to array[10] of pointer to int
```

Learn to read such declarations using the spiral/right‑left rule.

4.3 The restrict Keyword (C99)

A promise to the compiler that for the lifetime of the pointer, only it (or a pointer derived from it) will be used to access the pointed object. Enables aggressive optimisations.

```c
void memcpy(void *restrict dest, const void *restrict src, size_t n);
```

4.4 Inline Assembly

Not part of standard C, but supported via compiler extensions (GCC’s __asm__). Used for hardware‑specific instructions.

4.5 Multithreading

POSIX threads (pthread) or C11 <threads.h>. Topics include:

· Race conditions and data races.
· Mutexes, condition variables.
· Atomic operations (<stdatomic.h> in C11).

```c
#include <pthread.h>
pthread_t thread;
pthread_create(&thread, NULL, thread_func, NULL);
pthread_join(thread, NULL);
```

volatile does not guarantee atomicity or ordering.

4.6 Setjmp / Longjmp

Non‑local jumps that can be used for error handling in C. They skip normal stack unwinding; very dangerous and rarely used in modern code.

4.7 Custom Allocators

For performance‑sensitive applications, you can create memory pools using a large static buffer and a free list to avoid malloc overhead.

4.8 Debugging & Analysis Tools

· gdb: breakpoints, stack traces, watchpoints.
· Valgrind: memory leaks, invalid accesses.
· AddressSanitizer (-fsanitize=address): detects memory corruption.
· UndefinedBehaviourSanitizer (-fsanitize=undefined): catches UB at runtime.
· perf / gprof: performance profiling.

4.9 Writing Portable Code

· Use fixed‑width types from <stdint.h>.
· Avoid assumptions about size of int, sign of char.
· Don’t rely on implementation‑defined behaviour.
· Test on multiple compilers/platforms.

